---
layout: default
title: Language Den - The Vocabulary App Built for Language Learners
---

<% cta_button = capture do %>
  <% if site.metadata.app_store_url && !site.metadata.app_store_url.empty? %>
  <a href="<%= site.metadata.app_store_url %>" class="btn-primary">Download Free on the App Store</a>
  <% else %>
  <span class="btn-primary btn-coming-soon">Coming Soon to the App Store</span>
  <% end %>
<% end %>

<main>
  <!-- Hero -->
  <section class="hero">
    <div class="hero-container">
      <div class="hero-badge">Free on iOS</div>
      <h1 class="hero-headline">Finally, a vocabulary app that<br><span class="gradient-text">gets language learning right.</span></h1>
      <p class="hero-sub">Language Den is the only vocabulary app built from the ground up for language learners. Spaced repetition that actually works. Flashcards that understand how languages work. And it's completely free.</p>
      <div class="hero-actions">
        <%= cta_button %>
      </div>
      <p class="hero-footnote">Free forever. No account required. No ads. No tracking. No catch.</p>

      <div class="screenshot-group screenshot-group--hero">
        <div class="screenshot-filled">
          <img src="/images/home-details.png" alt="Language Den home dashboard with review stats and mastery levels">
        </div>
        <div class="screenshot-filled">
          <img src="/images/review.png" alt="Language Den flashcard review in progress">
        </div>
        <div class="screenshot-filled">
          <img src="/images/word-detail.png" alt="Language Den word detail with definition and example sentence">
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Open with pain -->
  <section class="longform-section">
    <div class="longform-container longform-container--narrow">
      <h2 class="longform-heading">Let's be honest. You've tried other apps. They didn't work.</h2>
      <p class="longform-body">You downloaded Duolingo. You kept the streak going for a while. But then you realized you were spending 20 minutes a day matching pictures to words you already knew. You weren't learning. You were playing a game.</p>
      <p class="longform-body">Maybe you tried Anki. People on Reddit swear by it. So you downloaded it, opened it up, and... stared at a screen that looks like it was designed in 2006. Because it was. You tried to make a card. Then you had to learn about "note types" and "card templates" and "deck options." You just wanted to learn some vocabulary.</p>
      <p class="longform-body">Or maybe Quizlet. Clean interface. Easy to use. You made some flashcards, studied them, felt great. Two weeks later? Gone. All of it. Because Quizlet has no spaced repetition. It's a tool for cramming before an exam, not for actually learning a language.</p>
      <p class="longform-body">Sound familiar?</p>
      <p class="longform-body"><strong>The problem isn't you. The problem is that none of these tools were built for what you're actually trying to do.</strong></p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Agitate -->
  <section class="longform-section longform-section--alt">
    <div class="longform-container longform-container--narrow">
      <h2 class="longform-heading">Think about how much time you've already wasted</h2>
      <p class="longform-body">Hours configuring Anki decks instead of actually studying. Days maintaining a Duolingo streak that taught you nothing useful. Weeks re-learning the same words on Quizlet because they never stuck in the first place.</p>
      <p class="longform-body">And here's the worst part: you <em>know</em> how you should be learning vocabulary. You know spaced repetition works. You know flashcards are effective. You just haven't found an app that does it right for language learning.</p>

      <div class="highlight-box">
        <p>Every day you spend fighting the wrong tools is a day you could have spent actually building your vocabulary.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Introduce the solution -->
  <section class="longform-section longform-section--accent">
    <div class="longform-container longform-container--narrow">
      <h2 class="longform-heading">There's a better way. It's called Language Den.</h2>
      <p class="longform-body">Language Den is a vocabulary app built exclusively for language learners. Not a generic flashcard tool that you have to bend into shape. Not a game that wastes your time. A focused, purpose-built app for one thing: <strong>helping you learn and remember vocabulary in any language.</strong></p>
      <p class="longform-body">Every feature exists because language learners need it. Nothing exists because a product manager thought it would look good on a feature list.</p>
      <div class="inline-cta">
        <%= cta_button %>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- What makes it different -->
  <section class="longform-section">
    <div class="longform-container longform-container--narrow">
      <h2 class="longform-heading">Here's what makes Language Den different from everything else</h2>

      <div class="sales-point">
        <h3 class="sales-point-heading">Spaced repetition that actually works (without a manual)</h3>
        <p class="longform-body">Spaced repetition is the single most effective technique for long-term memorization. This isn't debated. It's settled science. The problem is that most apps either don't have it (Quizlet) or make you configure it yourself (Anki).</p>
        <p class="longform-body">Language Den uses FSRS, a modern algorithm that's more accurate than what Anki has used for the past 20 years. It tracks how well you know each word and schedules your reviews at the exact moment you're about to forget.</p>
        <p class="longform-body">You don't configure anything. You don't tweak settings. You don't install add-ons. You just review your cards and the app handles everything else.</p>
        <p class="longform-body"><strong>Result: you remember more words while spending less time studying.</strong></p>

        <div class="screenshot-single">
          <div class="screenshot-filled">
            <img src="/images/review-card-ratings.png" alt="Language Den review screen showing spaced repetition rating buttons">
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="section-divider"></div>

      <div class="sales-point">
        <h3 class="sales-point-heading">Any language you can type. Seriously, any.</h3>
        <p class="longform-body">Duolingo supports about 40 languages. Sounds like a lot until you realize yours isn't on the list. Even if it is, you're stuck with their curriculum. You can't learn your own words.</p>
        <p class="longform-body">Anki technically supports everything, but you have to find or build all the content yourself.</p>
        <p class="longform-body">Language Den works with any language you can type. Spanish, Japanese, Arabic, Korean, Swahili, Welsh, Tagalog, Uzbek, Navajo, Esperanto. It doesn't matter. There's no fixed list. If you can type it, you can learn it.</p>
        <p class="longform-body"><strong>Learning a less common language? You get the same experience as someone learning Spanish. No compromises.</strong></p>
        <div class="language-pills">
          <span>Spanish</span><span>Japanese</span><span>Arabic</span><span>Korean</span>
          <span>Mandarin</span><span>French</span><span>German</span><span>Thai</span>
          <span>Swahili</span><span>Portuguese</span><span>Russian</span><span>Hindi</span>
          <span>Italian</span><span>Turkish</span><span>Vietnamese</span><span>+ any other</span>
        </div>

        <div class="screenshot-single">
          <div class="screenshot-filled">
            <img src="/images/sources.png" alt="Language Den sources list for organizing vocabulary by textbook or course">
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="section-divider"></div>

      <div class="sales-point">
        <h3 class="sales-point-heading">Built specifically for how languages work</h3>
        <p class="longform-body">Anki doesn't know the difference between a vocabulary card and a geography card. Quizlet doesn't either. They're generic tools.</p>
        <p class="longform-body">Language Den understands that language learning has specific needs. Definitions in context. Natural example sentences. Conjugation patterns. Multiple card types so you can learn the same word from different angles.</p>
        <p class="longform-body"><strong>This is what "built for language learners" actually means. Every feature is designed around how you learn vocabulary, not how you memorize random facts.</strong></p>

        <div class="screenshot-pair">
          <div class="screenshot-filled">
            <img src="/images/flashcard.png" alt="Language Den word detail showing Production and Recognition card types">
          </div>
          <div class="screenshot-filled">
            <img src="/images/sub-section.png" alt="Language Den vocabulary organized by chapter with words and translations">
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="inline-cta">
        <%= cta_button %>
        <p class="inline-cta-note">Takes 30 seconds to get started. No account needed.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="section-divider"></div>

      <div class="sales-point">
        <h3 class="sales-point-heading">Never lose a word again</h3>
        <p class="longform-body">You're watching a show in your target language. Someone says a word you don't know. You think "I should look that up later." You never do. The word is gone forever.</p>
        <p class="longform-body">Language Den's Quick Notes fix this. Hear a new word? Open the app, type it in (or record the audio), and close it. Done. Two seconds. Later, when you have time, process your notes into full flashcards with a single tap.</p>
        <p class="longform-body"><strong>Every word you encounter becomes a word you can learn. Nothing slips through the cracks.</strong></p>

        <div class="screenshot-single">
          <div class="screenshot-filled">
            <img src="/images/quick-note.png" alt="Language Den Quick Notes screen with captured words ready to process">
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="section-divider"></div>

      <div class="sales-point">
        <h3 class="sales-point-heading">Images that make words stick</h3>
        <p class="longform-body">There's a concept in cognitive science called the "picture superiority effect." Your brain remembers images dramatically better than text. It's not even close.</p>
        <p class="longform-body">Language Den has built-in image search powered by Unsplash. Find a photo that captures the meaning of a word and attach it to your card. When you review, that visual anchor helps cement the word in your memory in a way that text alone never will.</p>

        <div class="screenshot-single">
          <div class="screenshot-filled">
            <img src="/images/source.png" alt="Language Den source detail showing chapters and sections for organized learning">
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="section-divider"></div>

      <div class="sales-point">
        <h3 class="sales-point-heading">Your data. Your device. Your iCloud. That's it.</h3>
        <p class="longform-body">Most apps want your email, your name, your usage data. They track what you study, when you study, and how you study. Then they sell that data or use it to push you toward a subscription.</p>
        <p class="longform-body">Language Den doesn't do any of that.</p>
        <p class="longform-body">There's no account to create. Your data syncs through your personal iCloud, and it never touches anyone else's servers. Start a review on your iPhone, finish it on your iPad. No ads. No tracking. No analytics SDKs.</p>
        <p class="longform-body"><strong>Just an app that does its job and leaves you alone.</strong></p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Comparison table -->
  <section class="longform-section longform-section--alt">
    <div class="longform-container">
      <h2 class="longform-heading" style="text-align: center;">Still not sure? Compare for yourself.</h2>
      <p class="longform-body" style="text-align: center; max-width: 600px; margin: 0 auto 40px;">Here's Language Den side by side with the tools you've probably already tried.</p>
      <div class="comparison-table-wrapper">
        <table class="comparison-table">
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th></th>
              <th class="comparison-highlight">Language Den</th>
              <th>Anki</th>
              <th>Duolingo</th>
              <th>Quizlet</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td>Spaced repetition</td>
              <td class="comparison-highlight">FSRS (latest algorithm)</td>
              <td>SM-2 / FSRS</td>
